/* CDPSE :: content/quiz4.js — CDPSE Domain 4 question bank (100 items). */
window.CDPSE = window.CDPSE || {}; CDPSE.questions = CDPSE.questions || [];
CDPSE.questions.push.apply(CDPSE.questions, [
{"id":"D4-001","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"easy","q":"A privacy engineer is reviewing a legacy on-premises data center that stores regulated personal data. Which characteristic of legacy infrastructure MOST commonly complicates privacy engineering efforts?","options":["Monolithic architectures with data flows that are poorly documented and hard to trace","Elastic auto-scaling that provisions resources on demand","Built-in encryption enabled by default across all storage tiers","Fine-grained tagging of every data element at creation time"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Monolithic architectures with data flows that are poorly documented and hard to trace</strong> — legacy platforms were frequently built before privacy-by-design practices existed, so data lineage, interdependencies, and personal data locations are often undocumented, making privacy controls difficult to apply accurately.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Elastic auto-scaling that provisions resources on demand</b>: this is a cloud-native characteristic, not a trait of legacy infrastructure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Built-in encryption enabled by default across all storage tiers</b>: legacy systems commonly lack default encryption; this describes a modern, well-engineered platform.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Fine-grained tagging of every data element at creation time</b>: this is a privacy-engineering best practice rarely found in legacy environments, which is precisely the gap engineers must close.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-002","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"easy","q":"An organization is migrating a legacy mainframe application that processes personal data to a modern platform. Which action should the privacy engineer take FIRST?","options":["Immediately encrypt the mainframe's production database","Conduct a data discovery and mapping exercise to identify where personal data resides and how it flows","Delete all data older than seven years","Purchase a new data loss prevention tool"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Conduct a data discovery and mapping exercise to identify where personal data resides and how it flows</strong> — before any technical control or migration decision can be made responsibly, the engineer must understand what personal data exists, where it lives, and how it moves through the legacy system.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Immediately encrypt the mainframe's production database</b>: encryption is a sound control but premature without first knowing what data needs protecting and where it resides.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delete all data older than seven years</b>: deletion decisions require a retention policy and legal review, not a default first step.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Purchase a new data loss prevention tool</b>: tooling decisions should follow, not precede, an understanding of the actual data landscape.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-003","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"easy","q":"Under the cloud shared responsibility model for an Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) offering, which privacy-related task remains the customer's responsibility?","options":["Physical security of the data center facility","Patching the hypervisor firmware","Classifying and applying access controls to the data the customer uploads","Maintaining the physical network cabling"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Classifying and applying access controls to the data the customer uploads</strong> — in IaaS, the cloud provider secures the underlying infrastructure, but the customer remains responsible for the data itself, including classification, access management, and configuration of privacy controls.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Physical security of the data center facility</b>: this is the provider's responsibility under IaaS, as the customer never has physical access to the hardware.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Patching the hypervisor firmware</b>: the hypervisor and underlying virtualization layer are managed by the provider in IaaS.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Maintaining the physical network cabling</b>: physical network infrastructure is owned and maintained entirely by the provider.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-004","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"med","q":"A company uses a Software as a Service (SaaS) CRM platform to store customer personal data. Under the shared responsibility model, which privacy obligation remains with the customer organization?","options":["Writing the SaaS application's source code","Patching the SaaS application's underlying operating system","Maintaining the SaaS vendor's data center HVAC systems","Ensuring lawful basis for processing and configuring user-level access permissions appropriately"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Ensuring lawful basis for processing and configuring user-level access permissions appropriately</strong> — even in SaaS, where the provider manages nearly the entire technology stack, the customer remains accountable for how it uses the service, including legal basis for processing and proper configuration of access and sharing settings.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Patching the SaaS application's underlying operating system</b>: in SaaS, the provider manages the full stack, including the OS and application code.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Maintaining the SaaS vendor's data center HVAC systems</b>: physical facility upkeep is entirely the provider's responsibility.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Writing the SaaS application's source code</b>: the vendor owns and develops the application; the customer only configures and uses it.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-005","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"easy","q":"An organization is implementing a bring-your-own-device (BYOD) program. Which control BEST reduces the privacy risk of corporate personal data being exposed on a lost or stolen personal device?","options":["Remote wipe capability for the corporate data container via mobile device management (MDM)","Requiring employees to use the same password for all accounts","Disabling all encryption to speed up file access","Allowing unrestricted USB data transfer to any device"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Remote wipe capability for the corporate data container via mobile device management (MDM)</strong> — MDM/containerization lets an organization remotely wipe only the corporate data partition on a lost or stolen device, protecting personal data without erasing the employee's personal content.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Requiring employees to use the same password for all accounts</b>: password reuse is a security anti-pattern that increases, rather than decreases, risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling all encryption to speed up file access</b>: removing encryption directly increases the exposure of data if the device is lost.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allowing unrestricted USB data transfer to any device</b>: unrestricted transfer increases the risk of uncontrolled data exfiltration.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-006","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"med","q":"An organization issues IoT sensors that collect location data from field technicians' vehicles. Which endpoint privacy control is MOST important to implement?","options":["Maximizing GPS sampling frequency to once per second regardless of use case","Data minimization at the point of collection, capturing only the location precision actually needed","Storing raw location data indefinitely on the device for later analysis","Disabling all firmware updates to avoid altering the sensor's behavior"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Data minimization at the point of collection, capturing only the location precision actually needed</strong> — endpoint privacy engineering should limit the granularity and frequency of collected data to what is strictly necessary for the business purpose, reducing exposure if the device or data is compromised.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Maximizing GPS sampling frequency to once per second regardless of use case</b>: excessive sampling creates unnecessary granular tracking data, increasing privacy risk without a demonstrated need.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Storing raw location data indefinitely on the device for later analysis</b>: indefinite on-device retention increases exposure and violates data minimization and retention principles.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling all firmware updates to avoid altering the sensor's behavior</b>: skipping firmware updates leaves known vulnerabilities unpatched, increasing risk rather than protecting privacy.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-007","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"easy","q":"Which network control BEST supports privacy by limiting an attacker's ability to move laterally and access personal data stores after compromising one segment?","options":["Disabling all firewall logging","Using a single flat network for all systems","Network segmentation and micro-segmentation","Allowing all outbound traffic without restriction"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Network segmentation and micro-segmentation</strong> — dividing the network into isolated zones limits lateral movement, so a breach in one segment does not automatically expose personal data held in other segments.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Using a single flat network for all systems</b>: a flat network allows unrestricted lateral movement, the opposite of the desired control.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling all firewall logging</b>: disabling logging removes visibility into traffic and incidents, harming both security and privacy monitoring.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allowing all outbound traffic without restriction</b>: unrestricted outbound traffic increases the risk of undetected data exfiltration.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-008","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"hard","q":"A privacy engineer is designing network controls for a system that processes special-category health data. The system must communicate with an external analytics partner. Which architecture BEST balances connectivity needs with privacy risk reduction?","options":["Sharing the same broad network segment used by all other business partners","A fully open internet-facing API endpoint with no IP restrictions","Disabling all network connectivity entirely to eliminate risk","A dedicated, tightly scoped VPN or private link restricted to only the specific ports, protocols, and endpoints required, combined with egress filtering"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A dedicated, tightly scoped VPN or private link restricted to only the specific ports, protocols, and endpoints required, combined with egress filtering</strong> — this approach applies least-privilege network design, enabling necessary connectivity while strictly limiting what can be sent where, reducing the attack surface for sensitive health data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A fully open internet-facing API endpoint with no IP restrictions</b>: this exposes sensitive data to the broadest possible attack surface, contrary to risk reduction.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling all network connectivity entirely to eliminate risk</b>: this fails the stated business requirement of connecting with the analytics partner.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Sharing the same broad network segment used by all other business partners</b>: broad shared segments increase exposure to unrelated third parties, violating least privilege.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-009","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"easy","q":"Applying Privacy by Design principles during the software development lifecycle means privacy requirements should be:","options":["Embedded from the initial design phase, not added after deployment","Considered only after a data breach occurs","Left entirely to the legal department post-launch","Addressed only if a customer complaint is received"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Embedded from the initial design phase, not added after deployment</strong> — Privacy by Design requires proactively building privacy considerations into architecture and requirements from the earliest stages, rather than retrofitting controls after the system is built.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Considered only after a data breach occurs</b>: this is a reactive approach that defeats the proactive intent of Privacy by Design.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Left entirely to the legal department post-launch</b>: privacy engineering requires cross-functional involvement throughout development, not a legal-only afterthought.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Addressed only if a customer complaint is received</b>: waiting for complaints means privacy failures have already occurred and been experienced by users.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-010","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"hard","q":"A development team is using LINDDUN threat modeling during the design phase of a new messaging application. Which threat category in LINDDUN addresses the risk that a user's actions can be tied back to their real identity across multiple sessions?","options":["Non-repudiation","Linkability","Detectability","Disclosure of information"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Linkability</strong> — this LINDDUN category specifically addresses the risk that two or more items of interest (such as user actions or sessions) can be linked together, potentially revealing more about an individual than intended.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Non-repudiation</b>: in LINDDUN this represents a threat where a user cannot deny having performed an action, which is a distinct concern from linking sessions to an identity.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Detectability</b>: this concerns whether the existence of an item of interest (such as a user's participation) can be distinguished, not whether identities can be linked.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disclosure of information</b>: this concerns the exposure of information content itself, not the linking of separate data points to an identity.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-011","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"hard","q":"During a LINDDUN threat modeling session, the team identifies that an adversary could observe encrypted traffic patterns to infer that a specific user is using a whistleblower reporting feature, even without decrypting the content. Which LINDDUN threat category BEST describes this risk?","options":["Non-compliance","Identifiability","Detectability","Unawareness"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Detectability</strong> — this category addresses the risk that an attacker can distinguish whether an item of interest (such as use of a specific sensitive feature) exists or is occurring, even without accessing its content, which matches the traffic-pattern inference described.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Identifiability</b>: this concerns whether a specific individual can be singled out or identified, not merely whether an activity's existence can be detected.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Non-compliance</b>: this LINDDUN category addresses failure to adhere to legislation, policy, or user expectations, not traffic-pattern inference.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Unawareness</b>: this concerns users being insufficiently informed about data processing, unrelated to inferring feature usage from traffic patterns.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-012","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"easy","q":"When designing an API that returns customer profile data to a partner application, which practice BEST supports data minimization?","options":["Caching full responses indefinitely on the partner's servers","Returning the entire customer database table for every request","Requiring no authentication so integration is easier","Returning only the specific fields the partner's use case requires, rather than the full customer record"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Returning only the specific fields the partner's use case requires, rather than the full customer record</strong> — designing APIs to expose only the minimum necessary fields directly implements data minimization and limits the impact if the partner's systems are compromised.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Returning the entire customer database table for every request</b>: this over-shares data far beyond what is needed, increasing exposure risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Requiring no authentication so integration is easier</b>: removing authentication eliminates access control, a serious security and privacy failure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Caching full responses indefinitely on the partner's servers</b>: indefinite caching of full responses increases retention risk and violates minimization principles.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-013","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"med","q":"A cloud-native application uses containerized microservices, each with access to different subsets of customer data. Which design principle BEST reduces privacy risk in this architecture?","options":["Granting each microservice only the specific data access and permissions it needs to perform its function","Granting every microservice full administrative access to the shared database for convenience","Hardcoding database credentials into each container image","Disabling network policies between containers to simplify troubleshooting"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Granting each microservice only the specific data access and permissions it needs to perform its function</strong> — applying least privilege at the microservice level ensures that a compromised or misconfigured service cannot access data beyond its intended scope.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Granting every microservice full administrative access to the shared database for convenience</b>: this violates least privilege and dramatically expands the blast radius of any single compromised service.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Hardcoding database credentials into each container image</b>: hardcoded credentials are a serious security risk and complicate credential rotation.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling network policies between containers to simplify troubleshooting</b>: removing network policies eliminates segmentation controls that limit lateral movement between services.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-014","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"easy","q":"Which activity is a core component of effective privacy-related asset management?","options":["Deleting the asset inventory once a system is decommissioned without further review","Maintaining an inventory of systems and data stores that process personal data","Tracking only physical assets and ignoring cloud-hosted resources","Allowing each business unit to maintain a private, undisclosed asset list"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Maintaining an inventory of systems and data stores that process personal data</strong> — an accurate, current inventory is foundational to privacy engineering because it enables the organization to know where personal data lives, apply controls, and respond effectively to requests or incidents.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Deleting the asset inventory once a system is decommissioned without further review</b>: decommissioning still requires verifying data disposition, not simply discarding inventory records.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Tracking only physical assets and ignoring cloud-hosted resources</b>: modern environments require inventorying cloud assets as thoroughly as on-premises ones.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allowing each business unit to maintain a private, undisclosed asset list</b>: siloed, undisclosed inventories undermine enterprise-wide visibility and governance.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-015","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"med","q":"An organization discovers an unregistered database server storing customer personal data that was never added to the asset inventory. What is the GREATEST privacy risk this represents?","options":["The server may not match the corporate branding guidelines","The server likely uses a faster storage technology than approved systems","The organization cannot ensure appropriate controls, retention, and subject rights are applied to data it does not know exists","The unregistered server increases the electricity bill"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The organization cannot ensure appropriate controls, retention, and subject rights are applied to data it does not know exists</strong> — untracked ('shadow') data stores fall outside governance processes, meaning encryption, access control, retention, and data subject request fulfillment cannot be reliably applied.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The server likely uses a faster storage technology than approved systems</b>: performance characteristics are irrelevant to the privacy risk of an unmanaged asset.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The server may not match the corporate branding guidelines</b>: branding is a cosmetic concern, not a privacy risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The unregistered server increases the electricity bill</b>: cost is a minor operational concern, not the primary privacy risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-016","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"easy","q":"Which access control model assigns permissions to users based on their job function within the organization?","options":["Public access with no restrictions","Discretionary access control granted by any user","Mandatory physical-only access with no digital component","Role-based access control (RBAC)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Role-based access control (RBAC)</strong> — RBAC assigns permissions according to predefined roles that reflect job functions, ensuring users only receive access appropriate to their responsibilities.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Discretionary access control granted by any user</b>: this describes a different model where resource owners grant access at their discretion, not one based on job function roles.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Mandatory physical-only access with no digital component</b>: this describes a physical security control unrelated to how digital system permissions are assigned.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Public access with no restrictions</b>: unrestricted public access is the opposite of a controlled, role-based approach.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-017","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"easy","q":"An organization wants to grant access to sensitive records based on dynamic attributes such as department, data classification, and time of day, rather than fixed job titles. Which access control model BEST supports this requirement?","options":["Attribute-based access control (ABAC)","Simple role-based access control (RBAC) only","No access control, relying solely on physical security","A single shared administrator account for all users"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Attribute-based access control (ABAC)</strong> — ABAC evaluates multiple contextual attributes (user, resource, environment) at the time of the access request, enabling fine-grained, dynamic decisions beyond what static roles alone can provide.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Simple role-based access control (RBAC) only</b>: pure RBAC assigns fixed permissions per role and does not natively evaluate dynamic contextual attributes like time of day.</span> <span class='qd'><b>No access control, relying solely on physical security</b>: physical security alone does nothing to restrict digital access to sensitive records.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A single shared administrator account for all users</b>: shared accounts eliminate accountability and violate least privilege entirely.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-018","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"hard","q":"A financial services firm wants to enforce that a loan officer can only view a customer's full Social Security number if the officer is actively assigned to that customer's open loan application, during business hours, from a corporate-managed device. Which access control approach BEST enables this level of granularity?","options":["A static role that grants all loan officers permanent access to all customer SSNs","Attribute-based access control (ABAC) combining identity, resource context, and environmental conditions","Removing authentication entirely for internal staff to speed up processing","Mandatory access control based solely on security clearance levels"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Attribute-based access control (ABAC) combining identity, resource context, and environmental conditions</strong> — this scenario requires evaluating multiple simultaneous conditions (assignment, time, device trust), which is precisely what ABAC policies are designed to enforce dynamically.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A static role that grants all loan officers permanent access to all customer SSNs</b>: a static role cannot express the conditional, context-dependent restrictions described and grants excessive standing access.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Removing authentication entirely for internal staff to speed up processing</b>: removing authentication eliminates any ability to enforce these conditions and is a severe security failure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Mandatory access control based solely on security clearance levels</b>: clearance-only models do not account for assignment, time, or device-based conditions described in the scenario.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-019","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"easy","q":"Which authentication factor category does a fingerprint scan belong to?","options":["Something you have","Something you know","Something you are (inherence)","Somewhere you are"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Something you are (inherence)</strong> — biometric characteristics like fingerprints are classified as inherence factors because they are intrinsic physical traits of the individual.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Something you know</b>: this factor category covers knowledge-based credentials such as passwords or PINs, not physical traits.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Something you have</b>: this covers possession-based factors such as hardware tokens or smart cards, not biometrics.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Somewhere you are</b>: location is sometimes used as a contextual signal but is not a standard authentication factor category alongside knowledge, possession, and inherence.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-020","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"med","q":"An organization wants to reduce the risk of account takeover for systems storing personal data. Which control provides the STRONGEST improvement to authentication assurance?","options":["Disabling account lockout entirely","Increasing the minimum password length by one character","Allowing unlimited failed login attempts to improve user convenience","Enforcing multi-factor authentication (MFA) combining at least two independent factor categories"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Enforcing multi-factor authentication (MFA) combining at least two independent factor categories</strong> — MFA significantly raises the difficulty of account takeover because an attacker must compromise multiple independent factors rather than a single credential.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Increasing the minimum password length by one character</b>: a marginal length increase provides only a small improvement compared to adding an independent authentication factor.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allowing unlimited failed login attempts to improve user convenience</b>: this actually increases risk by enabling brute-force attacks without restriction.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling account lockout entirely</b>: removing lockout protections removes a key defense against credential-guessing attacks.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-021","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"easy","q":"The principle of least privilege states that users should be granted:","options":["Only the access necessary to perform their job duties, and nothing more","Full administrative access by default to reduce help desk tickets","Access to all systems in the organization regardless of role","Permanent access that never expires or is reviewed"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Only the access necessary to perform their job duties, and nothing more</strong> — least privilege minimizes the potential damage from compromised accounts or insider misuse by limiting each user's access to what is strictly required.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Full administrative access by default to reduce help desk tickets</b>: broad default access directly contradicts least privilege and significantly increases risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Access to all systems in the organization regardless of role</b>: unrestricted access ignores the principle that access should map to actual job need.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Permanent access that never expires or is reviewed</b>: access should be periodically reviewed and revoked when no longer needed, not granted permanently without review.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-022","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"med","q":"An employee transfers from the finance department to marketing. From a least-privilege and identity governance perspective, what should happen to their finance system access?","options":["It should be left unchanged so the employee can help finance in emergencies","It should be reviewed and revoked as part of the role change, replaced with access appropriate to the new role","It should be expanded to include marketing access on top of existing finance access","It should be transferred to their new manager's account instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It should be reviewed and revoked as part of the role change, replaced with access appropriate to the new role</strong> — proper identity lifecycle management requires access to be re-evaluated at each role transition, removing entitlements no longer needed and provisioning only what the new role requires.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>It should be left unchanged so the employee can help finance in emergencies</b>: retaining unnecessary access after a role change is a classic cause of privilege creep and violates least privilege.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It should be expanded to include marketing access on top of existing finance access</b>: stacking access from multiple roles increases risk rather than aligning access to current duties.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It should be transferred to their new manager's account instead</b>: transferring access to another individual's account is not a recognized or appropriate access management practice.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-023","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is a recommended hardening practice based on frameworks such as the CIS Benchmarks?","options":["Enabling every optional service to maximize functionality","Leaving all default vendor passwords unchanged for compatibility","Disabling or removing unnecessary default services and accounts on a system","Disabling all system logging to reduce disk usage"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Disabling or removing unnecessary default services and accounts on a system</strong> — CIS Benchmarks and similar hardening guidance recommend reducing the attack surface by removing default accounts, unused services, and unnecessary features that are not required for the system's function.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Leaving all default vendor passwords unchanged for compatibility</b>: default credentials are a well-known attack vector and should always be changed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Enabling every optional service to maximize functionality</b>: enabling unnecessary services increases the attack surface rather than reducing it.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling all system logging to reduce disk usage</b>: disabling logging removes critical visibility needed for security monitoring and incident response.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-024","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"hard","q":"An organization's vulnerability scans repeatedly show critical, unpatched vulnerabilities on servers that store personal data, even though patches have been available for months. Which process improvement would BEST address the underlying issue?","options":["Assigning patch responsibility informally with no defined ownership","Removing the vulnerability scanning tool so the reports stop appearing","Waiting for the next major OS upgrade to apply all patches at once","Establishing a formal, risk-based patch management program with defined timelines for critical vulnerabilities"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Establishing a formal, risk-based patch management program with defined timelines for critical vulnerabilities</strong> — a structured patch management process with clear ownership and SLAs tied to vulnerability severity ensures critical issues are remediated promptly rather than persisting indefinitely.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Removing the vulnerability scanning tool so the reports stop appearing</b>: this eliminates visibility into risk without addressing the actual vulnerabilities, making the situation worse.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Waiting for the next major OS upgrade to apply all patches at once</b>: this leaves known critical vulnerabilities exposed for an extended, undefined period.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Assigning patch responsibility informally with no defined ownership</b>: lack of clear ownership is often the root cause of delayed patching and would not resolve the problem.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-025","domain":4,"obj":"4B6","diff":"easy","q":"Which transport protocol provides encryption for data in transit between a web browser and a server?","options":["Transport Layer Security (TLS)","File Transfer Protocol (FTP) without encryption","Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) without encryption","Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Transport Layer Security (TLS)</strong> — TLS encrypts data in transit between a client and server, protecting confidentiality and integrity of communications such as HTTPS web traffic.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>File Transfer Protocol (FTP) without encryption</b>: plain FTP transmits data, including credentials, in cleartext and provides no encryption.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) without encryption</b>: base SMTP does not encrypt message content unless paired with an extension like STARTTLS.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)</b>: ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses at the network layer and has no encryption function.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-026","domain":4,"obj":"4B6","diff":"med","q":"A privacy engineer wants to ensure that two internal microservices mutually verify each other's identity before exchanging personal data, rather than relying on network location alone. Which mechanism BEST achieves this?","options":["A shared static API key embedded in both services' source code","Mutual TLS (mTLS) with certificate-based authentication on both endpoints","Allowing traffic based solely on internal IP address range","Disabling authentication because both services are on the same internal network"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Mutual TLS (mTLS) with certificate-based authentication on both endpoints</strong> — mTLS requires both the client and server to present valid certificates, providing strong, verifiable identity assurance for both parties rather than trusting network location alone (a zero-trust approach).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A shared static API key embedded in both services' source code</b>: a shared static key is weaker than certificate-based mutual authentication and creates risk if the key is exposed in source code.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allowing traffic based solely on internal IP address range</b>: relying on network location assumes internal trust and is vulnerable to lateral movement from a compromised host.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling authentication because both services are on the same internal network</b>: this contradicts zero-trust principles and leaves the connection unauthenticated.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-027","domain":4,"obj":"4B7","diff":"easy","q":"Which term describes the process of converting readable data (plaintext) into an unreadable form (ciphertext) using a key?","options":["Anonymization","Tokenization","Encryption","Masking"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Encryption</strong> — encryption transforms plaintext into ciphertext using a cryptographic algorithm and key, and the original data can be recovered by decrypting with the appropriate key.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Tokenization</b>: tokenization replaces sensitive data with a non-sensitive substitute token mapped in a separate vault, which is a different mechanism than cryptographic transformation.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Anonymization</b>: anonymization irreversibly removes identifying characteristics so data can no longer be linked to an individual, unlike encryption which is reversible with a key.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Masking</b>: masking obscures portions of data (such as showing only the last four digits) typically for display purposes, not full cryptographic transformation.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-028","domain":4,"obj":"4B7","diff":"med","q":"An organization stores encryption keys for its database on the same server as the encrypted database itself. What is the GREATEST privacy risk this practice introduces?","options":["Local key storage is not compatible with any encryption algorithm","The keys will expire faster when stored locally","The database will run more slowly due to key storage overhead","An attacker who compromises the server gains access to both the encrypted data and the means to decrypt it"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>An attacker who compromises the server gains access to both the encrypted data and the means to decrypt it</strong> — proper key management separates keys from the data they protect (often using a dedicated key management system or HSM), so that compromising the data store alone does not also expose the decryption key.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The keys will expire faster when stored locally</b>: key expiration is governed by key rotation policy, not physical storage location.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The database will run more slowly due to key storage overhead</b>: performance is not the primary privacy concern in this scenario; the co-location of keys and data is.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Local key storage is not compatible with any encryption algorithm</b>: this is factually incorrect; local storage is technically compatible with encryption algorithms, it is simply a poor security practice.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-029","domain":4,"obj":"4B7","diff":"hard","q":"A privacy engineer is designing a key management strategy for a system handling highly sensitive biometric templates. Which architecture provides the STRONGEST protection for the encryption keys themselves?","options":["A hardware security module (HSM) that generates, stores, and uses keys without ever exposing them in plaintext outside the hardware boundary","Storing keys in a plaintext configuration file included in version control","Emailing the key to each administrator for backup purposes","Using the same key indefinitely across all systems with no rotation policy"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A hardware security module (HSM) that generates, stores, and uses keys without ever exposing them in plaintext outside the hardware boundary</strong> — HSMs are purpose-built, tamper-resistant devices that protect keys from extraction even if the surrounding system is compromised, providing the highest assurance for highly sensitive key material.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Storing keys in a plaintext configuration file included in version control</b>: this exposes the key to anyone with repository access, a severe and common real-world breach cause.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Emailing the key to each administrator for backup purposes</b>: transmitting key material over email creates uncontrolled copies and significant interception risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Using the same key indefinitely across all systems with no rotation policy</b>: lack of rotation increases the impact of any single key compromise and is considered poor key management practice.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-030","domain":4,"obj":"4B8","diff":"easy","q":"Which technique replaces a sensitive data element, such as a credit card number, with a randomly generated non-sensitive substitute value while retaining a secure mapping to the original in a separate vault?","options":["Hashing","Tokenization","Symmetric encryption","Anonymization"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Tokenization</strong> — tokenization substitutes sensitive values with a token that has no exploitable value outside the system, while a secure, separate token vault maintains the mapping needed to retrieve the original data when authorized.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Hashing</b>: hashing produces a fixed-length digest and, when unsalted, is not intended to be reversed to the original value via a lookup vault in the same way tokenization is.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Symmetric encryption</b>: encryption transforms data using a key and mathematical algorithm, not a token-to-value mapping table.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Anonymization</b>: anonymization is designed to be irreversible, whereas tokenization intentionally preserves a reversible mapping for authorized use.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-031","domain":4,"obj":"4B8","diff":"easy","q":"Which technique is BEST suited for securely storing passwords so that even if the storage is breached, the original passwords cannot practically be recovered?","options":["Reversible encryption using a key stored in the same database table","Storing passwords in plaintext for easy password recovery","Salted cryptographic hashing with a slow, purpose-built algorithm (e.g., bcrypt, Argon2)","Simple masking that displays only the first two characters"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Salted cryptographic hashing with a slow, purpose-built algorithm (e.g., bcrypt, Argon2)</strong> — salted, computationally expensive hashing functions are specifically designed for password storage, making brute-force and rainbow-table attacks impractical even if the hash database is exposed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Storing passwords in plaintext for easy password recovery</b>: plaintext storage immediately exposes all passwords upon any breach, which is a severe and well-known anti-pattern.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reversible encryption using a key stored in the same database table</b>: co-locating the decryption key with the encrypted passwords defeats the purpose of encryption if the database is compromised.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Simple masking that displays only the first two characters</b>: masking is a display-obfuscation technique, not a secure storage mechanism, and does not protect the underlying password value.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-032","domain":4,"obj":"4B8","diff":"med","q":"A customer service dashboard displays credit card numbers to support agents as '**** **** **** 1234' instead of the full number. Which technique is being applied?","options":["k-anonymity","Homomorphic encryption","Differential privacy","Data masking"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Data masking</strong> — masking obscures portions of a data value for display purposes (showing only the last four digits, for example) while the full value remains stored securely elsewhere, reducing exposure to those who do not need to see the complete value.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Homomorphic encryption</b>: this allows computation on encrypted data without decrypting it, unrelated to partially displaying a value on a dashboard.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Differential privacy</b>: this is a statistical technique that adds noise to query results or datasets, not a method for redacting individual displayed values.</span> <span class='qd'><b>k-anonymity</b>: this is a dataset-level anonymization guarantee ensuring each record is indistinguishable from at least k-1 others, not a single-field display technique.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-033","domain":4,"obj":"4C1","diff":"easy","q":"A security team configures application logs to record full customer records, including Social Security numbers and full credit card numbers, for every transaction. What is the PRIMARY privacy concern?","options":["Logs are creating an unnecessary, high-risk repository of sensitive personal data that expands the attack surface","Log files will take up too much disk space","The logs cannot be reviewed by developers","Log timestamps may not be synchronized correctly"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Logs are creating an unnecessary, high-risk repository of sensitive personal data that expands the attack surface</strong> — logs are often less protected than primary data stores and retained for troubleshooting, so capturing full sensitive fields multiplies the number of places that data must be secured and creates outsized breach exposure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Log files will take up too much disk space</b>: storage capacity is a minor operational concern, not the primary privacy risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The logs cannot be reviewed by developers</b>: reviewability is unrelated to the privacy exposure created by over-logging sensitive fields.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Log timestamps may not be synchronized correctly</b>: time synchronization is an operational/forensic concern, not the central privacy issue here.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-034","domain":4,"obj":"4C1","diff":"med","q":"Which practice BEST minimizes privacy risk when designing application logging for a system that processes personal data?","options":["Logging full personal data in every entry so nothing is ever missed during debugging","Masking or omitting sensitive fields in logs and logging only identifiers or references needed for troubleshooting","Sending all logs, including sensitive fields, to a public cloud storage bucket for convenience","Retaining all logs permanently with no defined retention period"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Masking or omitting sensitive fields in logs and logging only identifiers or references needed for troubleshooting</strong> — privacy-conscious logging design captures only what is operationally necessary, redacting or excluding sensitive personal data fields to reduce the risk surface of log repositories.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Logging full personal data in every entry so nothing is ever missed during debugging</b>: this maximizes exposure and directly contradicts data minimization principles.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Sending all logs, including sensitive fields, to a public cloud storage bucket for convenience</b>: publicly accessible storage for sensitive logs is a serious, avoidable exposure risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Retaining all logs permanently with no defined retention period</b>: indefinite retention without a policy violates data minimization and increases long-term breach exposure.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-035","domain":4,"obj":"4C2","diff":"easy","q":"Which mechanism allows a website visitor to record their choices about which categories of cookies (e.g., analytics, advertising) they permit?","options":["A hardware security module","A firewall access control list","A consent management platform (CMP)","A backup retention schedule"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A consent management platform (CMP)</strong> — a CMP presents cookie/tracking choices to users, records their consent preferences, and enforces those choices across the site's tags and scripts.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A firewall access control list</b>: firewall rules control network traffic flow, not user consent preferences for tracking technologies.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A hardware security module</b>: an HSM protects cryptographic keys and has no role in capturing website consent choices.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A backup retention schedule</b>: retention schedules govern how long backups are kept, unrelated to cookie consent management.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-036","domain":4,"obj":"4C2","diff":"hard","q":"A user has enabled the Global Privacy Control (GPC) signal in their browser. What is the MOST appropriate engineering response for a website that must honor this signal under applicable law?","options":["Disable the entire website for users who send a GPC signal","Ignore the GPC signal because it is only a proposed technical standard","Require the user to also submit a separate written opt-out request by mail before honoring GPC","Automatically treat the GPC signal as a valid opt-out of sale/sharing of personal data and suppress non-essential tracking accordingly"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Automatically treat the GPC signal as a valid opt-out of sale/sharing of personal data and suppress non-essential tracking accordingly</strong> — where legally recognized (such as under U.S. state privacy laws), GPC must be engineered as a legitimate universal opt-out mechanism, automatically applied without requiring additional manual steps from the user.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore the GPC signal because it is only a proposed technical standard</b>: several state privacy laws legally require honoring GPC as a valid opt-out signal, so ignoring it can create compliance exposure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Require the user to also submit a separate written opt-out request by mail before honoring GPC</b>: adding extra burdensome steps undermines the purpose of an automated universal opt-out signal and may violate applicable requirements.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disable the entire website for users who send a GPC signal</b>: this is a disproportionate and punitive response not required or supported by any privacy framework.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-037","domain":4,"obj":"4C2","diff":"hard","q":"An engineering team implements a consent banner but continues loading third-party advertising trackers before the user makes any choice. Under privacy-by-design expectations, what is the core engineering flaw?","options":["Trackers are firing prior to consent being obtained, so the technical implementation does not match the stated consent choice","The banner's button color does not meet accessibility contrast guidelines","The banner text is written in a font that is too small","The banner loads before the page's main content"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Trackers are firing prior to consent being obtained, so the technical implementation does not match the stated consent choice</strong> — a compliant consent implementation must technically block non-essential tracking scripts until affirmative consent is captured; firing trackers beforehand makes the consent mechanism illusory regardless of what the banner claims.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The banner's button color does not meet accessibility contrast guidelines</b>: accessibility contrast is a legitimate usability concern but not the core privacy engineering flaw described.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The banner text is written in a font that is too small</b>: font sizing is a cosmetic/usability issue, not the substantive failure of pre-consent tracking.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The banner loads before the page's main content</b>: load order of the banner itself is not the issue; the issue is trackers firing before consent is captured.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-038","domain":4,"obj":"4C3","diff":"easy","q":"Which anonymization technique ensures that each record in a dataset is indistinguishable from at least k-1 other records with respect to certain identifying attributes?","options":["Tokenization","k-anonymity","Symmetric encryption","Pseudonymization"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>k-anonymity</strong> — this model generalizes or suppresses quasi-identifiers so that every combination of attributes appears for at least k records, preventing any single individual from being singled out within that group.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Tokenization</b>: tokenization substitutes individual values with tokens and retains a reversible mapping, which does not provide the group-indistinguishability guarantee of k-anonymity.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Symmetric encryption</b>: encryption protects confidentiality via a key and is fully reversible, unlike the irreversible generalization used in k-anonymity.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Pseudonymization</b>: pseudonymization replaces identifiers with pseudonyms but the data remains linkable back to the individual with additional information, unlike true anonymization.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-039","domain":4,"obj":"4C3","diff":"med","q":"A dataset achieves k-anonymity, but an attacker notices that within one anonymized group, every individual shares the same rare medical diagnosis. What privacy weakness does this illustrate, which l-diversity is designed to address?","options":["The dataset was not pseudonymized before release","k-anonymity encrypts the data using a weak algorithm","Homogeneity of sensitive attribute values within a k-anonymous group can still reveal sensitive information despite quasi-identifier anonymity","The dataset violates data minimization because it has too many rows"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Homogeneity of sensitive attribute values within a k-anonymous group can still reveal sensitive information despite quasi-identifier anonymity</strong> — k-anonymity only protects against re-identification via quasi-identifiers; if every member of a group shares the same sensitive value, an attacker can infer that value for any individual known to be in the group, which is exactly the homogeneity attack l-diversity addresses by requiring diverse sensitive values within each group.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>k-anonymity encrypts the data using a weak algorithm</b>: k-anonymity is a generalization/suppression technique, not an encryption algorithm, so this option misdescribes the mechanism entirely.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The dataset was not pseudonymized before release</b>: pseudonymization is a separate, reversible technique and is not what l-diversity is designed to fix.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The dataset violates data minimization because it has too many rows</b>: row count is unrelated to the homogeneity attack described in the scenario.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-040","domain":4,"obj":"4C3","diff":"hard","q":"A researcher has both k-anonymity and l-diversity applied to a health dataset, yet is still able to narrow down an individual's likely diagnosis because the diverse sensitive values within a group are all clinically similar (e.g., different subtypes of the same disease). Which additional privacy model is designed to address this semantic closeness problem?","options":["Data loss prevention tagging","Symmetric key rotation","Role-based access control","t-closeness"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>t-closeness</strong> — t-closeness extends l-diversity by requiring that the distribution of sensitive attribute values within a group closely resembles the distribution in the overall dataset, addressing cases where diverse-but-semantically-similar values still leak meaningful information.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Symmetric key rotation</b>: this is a cryptographic key management practice, unrelated to statistical disclosure risk in anonymized datasets.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Role-based access control</b>: RBAC governs who can access a system or dataset, not the statistical properties of anonymized data itself.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Data loss prevention tagging</b>: DLP tagging identifies and controls sensitive data movement, not the semantic distribution of values within anonymized groups.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-041","domain":4,"obj":"4C4","diff":"easy","q":"Which statement correctly distinguishes pseudonymization from anonymization?","options":["Pseudonymization is reversible and the data remains personal data; anonymization is irreversible and removes personal data status","Pseudonymization and anonymization are identical processes with different names","Anonymization is reversible using a secret key, while pseudonymization is permanent","Pseudonymization always requires deleting the original identifiers permanently"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Pseudonymization is reversible and the data remains personal data; anonymization is irreversible and removes personal data status</strong> — pseudonymization replaces identifiers with pseudonyms while retaining a means (such as a separately held key or mapping table) to reverse the process, so the data still qualifies as personal data under most privacy laws; true anonymization removes this possibility entirely.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Pseudonymization and anonymization are identical processes with different names</b>: they are legally and technically distinct, with different reversibility properties and regulatory treatment.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Anonymization is reversible using a secret key, while pseudonymization is permanent</b>: this reverses the actual definitions of the two techniques.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Pseudonymization always requires deleting the original identifiers permanently</b>: pseudonymization specifically preserves the ability to re-link data using additional information kept separately, rather than permanently deleting identifiers.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-042","domain":4,"obj":"4C4","diff":"med","q":"A company replaces customer names in an analytics dataset with a consistent hashed customer ID, while keeping the mapping between hash and real identity in a separately secured table. Under most modern privacy laws, this dataset is BEST characterized as:","options":["Fully anonymized data with no further privacy obligations","Pseudonymized data that still constitutes personal data because re-identification remains possible","Data that is exempt from all privacy regulations because it uses a hash function","Encrypted data requiring no access controls on the hash mapping table"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Pseudonymized data that still constitutes personal data because re-identification remains possible</strong> — because a mapping table exists that can re-link the hashed IDs back to real identities, the dataset remains re-identifiable and continues to be regulated as personal data, even though direct identifiers are not visible in the analytics dataset itself.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Fully anonymized data with no further privacy obligations</b>: true anonymization requires that re-identification not be reasonably possible; the existence of a mapping table defeats that requirement.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Data that is exempt from all privacy regulations because it uses a hash function</b>: using a hash function alone does not exempt data from regulation when re-identification remains feasible via the retained mapping.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Encrypted data requiring no access controls on the hash mapping table</b>: the mapping table is highly sensitive and requires strong access controls; asserting none are needed is incorrect and risky.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-043","domain":4,"obj":"4C4","diff":"hard","q":"A privacy engineer must decide between pseudonymizing and fully anonymizing a dataset destined for a marketing analytics vendor. The business requires the ability to periodically refresh individual customer records with updated purchase history. Which approach is appropriate, and why?","options":["Neither is needed since the vendor is external and therefore not subject to privacy obligations","Anonymization, because it is always the stronger and preferred choice regardless of business requirements","Pseudonymization, because the business requirement to re-link and update records over time necessitates reversibility, unlike true anonymization","Full anonymization, because pseudonymized data can never be shared with third parties under any circumstances"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Pseudonymization, because the business requirement to re-link and update records over time necessitates reversibility, unlike true anonymization</strong> — since the use case explicitly requires periodically updating individual records, the data must remain linkable to specific individuals, which only pseudonymization supports; true anonymization would permanently sever that linkage and make record updates to specific individuals impossible.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Anonymization, because it is always the stronger and preferred choice regardless of business requirements</b>: anonymization is not universally 'better' when the business case requires ongoing re-identification for updates; the technique must fit the use case.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Neither is needed since the vendor is external and therefore not subject to privacy obligations</b>: sharing personal data with an external vendor does not eliminate privacy obligations; contractual and technical safeguards are still required.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Full anonymization, because pseudonymized data can never be shared with third parties under any circumstances</b>: pseudonymized data can be shared with appropriate contractual and technical safeguards; this option states an inaccurate absolute prohibition.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-044","domain":4,"obj":"4C5","diff":"easy","q":"Which privacy-enhancing technology (PET) allows computations to be performed directly on encrypted data, producing an encrypted result that, when decrypted, matches the result of performing the operation on the plaintext?","options":["Role-based access control","Data masking","k-anonymity","Homomorphic encryption"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Homomorphic encryption</strong> — this cryptographic technique enables mathematical operations on ciphertext such that the decrypted output equals the result of the same operations performed on the original plaintext, allowing data to be processed without ever being decrypted.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Data masking</b>: masking obscures values for display purposes and does not enable computation on the underlying encrypted values.</span> <span class='qd'><b>k-anonymity</b>: this is a dataset generalization technique for anonymization, not a method for computing on encrypted data.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Role-based access control</b>: RBAC is an authorization model, unrelated to performing computations on encrypted values.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-045","domain":4,"obj":"4C5","diff":"easy","q":"Multiple hospitals want to jointly compute aggregate statistics about a rare disease across their combined patient populations without any hospital revealing its individual patient-level data to the others. Which PET is BEST suited to this scenario?","options":["Secure multi-party computation (SMPC)","Simple database replication across all hospitals","A single shared spreadsheet emailed between hospitals","Standard symmetric encryption using one shared key for all data"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Secure multi-party computation (SMPC)</strong> — SMPC allows multiple parties to jointly compute a function over their combined inputs while each party's individual input remains private and is never revealed to the others, exactly matching this collaborative-analysis-without-disclosure requirement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Simple database replication across all hospitals</b>: replication would fully expose each hospital's raw patient-level data to all other participants, violating the confidentiality requirement.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A single shared spreadsheet emailed between hospitals</b>: this exposes raw data to all parties and offers no cryptographic privacy protection whatsoever.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Standard symmetric encryption using one shared key for all data</b>: shared-key encryption still requires someone to decrypt and see the raw data to compute statistics, defeating the goal of never revealing individual inputs.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-046","domain":4,"obj":"4C5","diff":"med","q":"A hospital wants to train a diagnostic machine learning model using data from thousands of patient devices without transferring any raw patient data off the devices to a central server. Which PET BEST supports this requirement?","options":["Full dataset centralization with encryption at rest only","Federated learning","Traditional client-server batch ETL of raw records","Manual de-identification followed by CSV export"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Federated learning</strong> — federated learning trains a shared model by sending model updates (not raw data) from each device to a central aggregator, keeping the underlying personal data local to each device throughout the process.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Full dataset centralization with encryption at rest only</b>: this still requires moving raw patient data off the devices, directly violating the stated requirement.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Traditional client-server batch ETL of raw records</b>: batch extraction of raw records also requires transferring the underlying personal data centrally.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Manual de-identification followed by CSV export</b>: this still involves exporting patient-derived data files rather than keeping data local as required.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-047","domain":4,"obj":"4C5","diff":"hard","q":"A data science team wants to release a public dataset for research while providing a mathematically provable bound on how much any single individual's data could influence the released statistics, even against an adversary with significant auxiliary information. Which technique BEST meets this requirement?","options":["Role-based access control applied to the published file","Simple field masking of the last name column only","Differential privacy, calibrating noise addition to a defined privacy budget (epsilon)","Basic pseudonymization of the record identifier"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Differential privacy, calibrating noise addition to a defined privacy budget (epsilon)</strong> — differential privacy provides a formal, mathematical guarantee that the inclusion or exclusion of any single individual's data has a bounded effect on the output, controlled by the epsilon privacy budget, which is precisely the provable protection required against adversaries with auxiliary knowledge.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Simple field masking of the last name column only</b>: masking one field provides no mathematical guarantee and leaves other quasi-identifiers and statistical inference risks unaddressed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Role-based access control applied to the published file</b>: access control restricts who can view the file but is irrelevant once the dataset itself is published for public research use.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Basic pseudonymization of the record identifier</b>: pseudonymization does not limit statistical inference about individuals within the released aggregate data and offers no formal privacy guarantee.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-048","domain":4,"obj":"4C5","diff":"med","q":"A company wants to test a new analytics feature using realistic-looking customer transaction data without exposing any actual customer records, even internally. Which approach BEST satisfies this need?","options":["Granting all developers direct access to the live production database","Using a production database export with all fields intact","Applying only field-level masking to a copy of the live production database","Generating synthetic data that statistically mirrors the real dataset's patterns without corresponding to any real individual"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Generating synthetic data that statistically mirrors the real dataset's patterns without corresponding to any real individual</strong> — synthetic data generation produces artificial records that preserve useful statistical properties for testing and development while containing no actual personal data, eliminating exposure risk entirely.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Using a production database export with all fields intact</b>: this directly exposes real customer personal data in a non-production/testing context, increasing risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Applying only field-level masking to a copy of the live production database</b>: masking a copy still involves handling real underlying data and may leave re-identification risk through remaining fields.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Granting all developers direct access to the live production database</b>: broad access to live production data for testing violates least privilege and data minimization principles.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-049","domain":4,"obj":"4C6","diff":"easy","q":"Which privacy risk is specifically associated with machine learning models that can be queried repeatedly by an adversary to determine whether a particular individual's record was part of the training dataset?","options":["Membership inference attack","Denial of service attack","SQL injection attack","Cross-site scripting attack"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Membership inference attack</strong> — this attack exploits differences in model behavior (such as confidence scores) to determine whether a specific data record was included in the training set, revealing sensitive information about the individuals whose data trained the model.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Denial of service attack</b>: this targets system availability by overwhelming resources, unrelated to inferring training data membership.</span> <span class='qd'><b>SQL injection attack</b>: this exploits improperly sanitized database queries in web applications, unrelated to ML model training data inference.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Cross-site scripting attack</b>: this involves injecting malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users, unrelated to ML model privacy attacks.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-050","domain":4,"obj":"4C6","diff":"hard","q":"An attacker queries a machine learning model repeatedly with crafted inputs and analyzes the outputs to reconstruct approximate features of a specific training record, such as a recognizable face from a facial recognition model. This describes which type of attack?","options":["Cross-site request forgery","Model inversion attack","Man-in-the-middle attack","Buffer overflow attack"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Model inversion attack</strong> — model inversion exploits a trained model's outputs to reconstruct representative input features associated with a class or specific record, potentially revealing sensitive characteristics of individuals in the training data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Cross-site request forgery</b>: this tricks an authenticated user's browser into submitting unwanted requests to a web application, unrelated to reconstructing model training data.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Man-in-the-middle attack</b>: this intercepts communications between two parties, unrelated to querying a model to reconstruct training features.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Buffer overflow attack</b>: this exploits memory management flaws to execute arbitrary code, unrelated to inferring model training data.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-051","domain":4,"obj":"4C6","diff":"hard","q":"A privacy engineer is reviewing an AI/ML pipeline for a customer-facing chatbot fine-tuned on internal support tickets that may contain personal data. Which combination of controls BEST mitigates both membership inference and model inversion risks?","options":["Allowing unlimited, unauthenticated API queries against the model to maximize usability","Publishing the full raw training dataset alongside the model for transparency","Applying differential privacy during training, minimizing sensitive fields in training data, and limiting model output granularity/confidence exposure","Disabling all monitoring of model query patterns to improve response latency"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Applying differential privacy during training, minimizing sensitive fields in training data, and limiting model output granularity/confidence exposure</strong> — combining privacy-preserving training techniques with data minimization and controlled output exposure directly reduces the signal an attacker can exploit for both membership inference and model inversion attacks.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Publishing the full raw training dataset alongside the model for transparency</b>: this directly exposes the sensitive personal data the mitigations are meant to protect, defeating the purpose entirely.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allowing unlimited, unauthenticated API queries against the model to maximize usability</b>: unrestricted querying gives attackers unlimited opportunity to probe the model for inference and inversion attacks.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling all monitoring of model query patterns to improve response latency</b>: removing monitoring eliminates the ability to detect abusive querying patterns indicative of an ongoing attack.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-052","domain":4,"obj":"4C7","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is a UNIQUE privacy challenge posed by biometric identifiers, such as fingerprints or facial scans, compared to traditional identifiers like passwords?","options":["Biometric identifiers are never considered personal data under any law","Biometric identifiers are always stored in plaintext by design","Biometric data cannot be used for authentication purposes","Biometric identifiers cannot be changed or reissued if compromised, unlike a password"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Biometric identifiers cannot be changed or reissued if compromised, unlike a password</strong> — a person cannot simply reset their fingerprint or facial geometry the way they can reset a password, so compromise of biometric data has permanent, irrevocable consequences, demanding especially strong protective controls.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Biometric identifiers are always stored in plaintext by design</b>: proper design stores biometric templates using encryption or irreversible transformation, not plaintext by default.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Biometric data cannot be used for authentication purposes</b>: biometric data is commonly and effectively used as an authentication factor, contradicting this option.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Biometric identifiers are never considered personal data under any law</b>: most modern privacy laws explicitly classify biometric data as sensitive personal data requiring heightened protection.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-053","domain":4,"obj":"4C7","diff":"med","q":"An organization is deploying IoT sensors in a smart building that continuously capture occupancy and movement data potentially tied to specific employees. Which privacy engineering control BEST addresses the emerging risk of this pervasive data collection?","options":["Aggregating or de-identifying occupancy data at the earliest processing stage so individual employees cannot be tracked over time","Streaming all raw sensor data indefinitely to a public analytics dashboard","Assigning a unique, unchanging identifier tied to each employee's badge for all sensor readings, with no aggregation","Disabling all data retention limits so historical movement can always be reconstructed"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Aggregating or de-identifying occupancy data at the earliest processing stage so individual employees cannot be tracked over time</strong> — processing pervasive IoT data at the point of collection to remove or aggregate individual-level detail limits the ability to profile or track specific employees, addressing the core privacy risk of continuous occupancy sensing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Streaming all raw sensor data indefinitely to a public analytics dashboard</b>: exposing raw, individually identifiable movement data publicly dramatically increases privacy risk rather than mitigating it.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Assigning a unique, unchanging identifier tied to each employee's badge for all sensor readings, with no aggregation</b>: a persistent identifier without aggregation enables long-term tracking of individuals, increasing rather than reducing risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling all data retention limits so historical movement can always be reconstructed</b>: unlimited retention of movement history increases exposure and violates data minimization and storage limitation principles.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-054","domain":4,"obj":"4C7","diff":"hard","q":"A supply chain consortium wants to use a blockchain to record product provenance, but some transaction metadata could indirectly reveal personal data about individual suppliers. Given blockchain's typically immutable and often widely replicated ledger, which privacy engineering approach is MOST appropriate?","options":["Store full personal data directly on the public blockchain since blockchain is inherently secure","Keep personal data off-chain in a separate, access-controlled system, storing only non-identifying references or hashes on-chain","Rely on the immutability of blockchain to guarantee compliance with data subject erasure rights","Avoid any data protection controls since blockchain participants are all trusted by default"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Keep personal data off-chain in a separate, access-controlled system, storing only non-identifying references or hashes on-chain</strong> — because on-chain data is typically immutable and widely replicated, personal data should be kept off-chain in systems that can support correction, access control, and erasure, with only non-identifying pointers or hashes recorded on the ledger.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Store full personal data directly on the public blockchain since blockchain is inherently secure</b>: security (integrity/availability) is not the same as privacy protection, and immutable public storage of personal data creates serious, permanent exposure and erasure conflicts.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Rely on the immutability of blockchain to guarantee compliance with data subject erasure rights</b>: immutability is fundamentally in tension with erasure rights, since data recorded on-chain typically cannot be deleted, creating a direct compliance conflict rather than guaranteeing it.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Avoid any data protection controls since blockchain participants are all trusted by default</b>: assuming universal trust among participants is an unfounded and risky assumption that ignores real privacy obligations.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-055","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"med","q":"A privacy engineer assessing a legacy system finds personal data replicated across multiple undocumented flat-file exports used by different departments for years. Which risk does this MOST directly create?","options":["Improved data quality due to redundancy","Faster query performance across all departments","Inconsistent application of retention, correction, and deletion obligations across untracked copies of the same data","Reduced storage costs from data duplication"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Inconsistent application of retention, correction, and deletion obligations across untracked copies of the same data</strong> — when personal data is duplicated across undocumented exports, honoring a correction or deletion request in the system of record does not guarantee the same action happens in every hidden copy, creating compliance and consistency gaps.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Faster query performance across all departments</b>: uncontrolled duplication is not a deliberate performance optimization and is not a benefit in this context.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Improved data quality due to redundancy</b>: untracked duplicate copies typically drift out of sync, degrading rather than improving data quality.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduced storage costs from data duplication</b>: duplication inherently increases, rather than reduces, storage consumption.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-056","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"hard","q":"An organization uses a Platform as a Service (PaaS) offering to host a custom application that processes personal data. During an incident, logs show unauthorized access resulted from a misconfigured application-level authorization check written by the organization's own developers. Under the shared responsibility model, who bears responsibility for this specific failure?","options":["The end users whose data was affected, because they agreed to the terms of service","The PaaS provider, because they are always responsible for all layers regardless of the model tier","No one, because cloud providers assume full liability for all incidents by default","The customer organization, because application-level code and configuration remain its responsibility in PaaS"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The customer organization, because application-level code and configuration remain its responsibility in PaaS</strong> — in PaaS, the provider manages the underlying platform and runtime, but the customer remains responsible for the application code it builds and deploys, including authorization logic; a flaw in custom authorization checks is squarely a customer responsibility.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The PaaS provider, because they are always responsible for all layers regardless of the model tier</b>: this contradicts the shared responsibility model, under which responsibility shifts depending on the service tier and the specific layer where the failure occurred.</span> <span class='qd'><b>No one, because cloud providers assume full liability for all incidents by default</b>: cloud providers do not assume blanket liability for customer-introduced application flaws.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The end users whose data was affected, because they agreed to the terms of service</b>: end users bear no responsibility for a flaw in the organization's own authorization code.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-057","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"easy","q":"An organization deploys wearable health-tracking devices to employees as part of a wellness program. Which endpoint privacy consideration is MOST important before collecting this data?","options":["Obtaining informed, voluntary consent and clearly scoping what health data is collected and how it will be used","Requiring every employee to participate as a condition of continued employment","Sharing raw health data with the employee's direct manager by default","Storing the data indefinitely with no defined retention or deletion process"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Obtaining informed, voluntary consent and clearly scoping what health data is collected and how it will be used</strong> — because wearable health data is highly sensitive and the workplace context carries an inherent power imbalance, voluntary, informed consent and clear purpose limitation are essential before collection begins.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Requiring every employee to participate as a condition of continued employment</b>: mandatory participation undermines the voluntariness of consent and raises significant fairness and legal concerns.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Sharing raw health data with the employee's direct manager by default</b>: default disclosure of sensitive health data to management violates purpose limitation and reasonable employee privacy expectations.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Storing the data indefinitely with no defined retention or deletion process</b>: indefinite retention without a defined policy violates data minimization and retention principles.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-058","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"med","q":"Which zero-trust network principle BEST reduces privacy risk by ensuring that access decisions are not based solely on whether a device is inside the corporate network perimeter?","options":["Granting unrestricted trust to any device once it connects to the internal Wi-Fi","Continuous verification of identity and device posture for every access request, regardless of network location","Treating the internal network as inherently safe once perimeter firewalls are in place","Allowing all internal traffic without any authentication"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Continuous verification of identity and device posture for every access request, regardless of network location</strong> — zero-trust architecture assumes no implicit trust based on network location and instead verifies identity, device health, and context for every request, limiting exposure of personal data even if perimeter defenses are breached.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Granting unrestricted trust to any device once it connects to the internal Wi-Fi</b>: this is the traditional perimeter-trust model that zero trust is specifically designed to replace.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Treating the internal network as inherently safe once perimeter firewalls are in place</b>: this assumption enables significant damage from insider threats or any device that breaches the perimeter.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allowing all internal traffic without any authentication</b>: unauthenticated internal traffic provides no verification and directly contradicts zero-trust principles.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-059","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"med","q":"During Privacy by Design reviews, LINDDUN's 'Non-compliance' threat category specifically evaluates whether a system:","options":["Uses too many external API calls","Encrypts data using an outdated algorithm","Fails to adhere to legislation, internal policy, or the privacy expectations communicated to users","Has slow database query performance"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Fails to adhere to legislation, internal policy, or the privacy expectations communicated to users</strong> — the Non-compliance category in LINDDUN captures the risk that a system's actual behavior diverges from applicable laws, organizational policy, or the privacy notices and promises made to data subjects.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Encrypts data using an outdated algorithm</b>: cryptographic algorithm strength is a security control weakness, not what the Non-compliance category specifically evaluates.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Uses too many external API calls</b>: API call volume is a performance/architecture concern unrelated to legal or policy compliance.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Has slow database query performance</b>: this is a performance issue, not a privacy compliance threat.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-060","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"hard","q":"A privacy engineer is reviewing a third-party API integration that receives more customer fields than the vendor's contract specifies it needs. Which principle is being violated?","options":["Multi-factor authentication requirements","Least privilege applied to network segmentation only","Encryption in transit requirements","Data minimization / purpose limitation, because more data is shared than necessary for the defined purpose"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Data minimization / purpose limitation, because more data is shared than necessary for the defined purpose</strong> — sharing fields beyond what a vendor's contracted purpose requires directly violates the principle that data collection and sharing should be limited to what is necessary for the specified purpose.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Least privilege applied to network segmentation only</b>: this scenario concerns data field scope in an API payload, not network segmentation specifically.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Encryption in transit requirements</b>: the issue described is about the scope of data shared, not whether the transmission channel is encrypted.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Multi-factor authentication requirements</b>: MFA concerns authentication strength, unrelated to the excessive data fields being transmitted.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-061","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST supports accurate classification of personal data assets across an enterprise?","options":["A data classification scheme integrated with the asset inventory, tagging systems by sensitivity level and data type","A single spreadsheet maintained manually once every five years","Relying solely on employees' informal knowledge of where sensitive data resides","Classifying data only after a breach has already occurred"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A data classification scheme integrated with the asset inventory, tagging systems by sensitivity level and data type</strong> — embedding classification directly into the asset inventory ensures that sensitivity levels are consistently tracked and can drive appropriate controls across the environment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A single spreadsheet maintained manually once every five years</b>: infrequent manual updates quickly become stale in a dynamic environment and fail to reflect current systems.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Relying solely on employees' informal knowledge of where sensitive data resides</b>: informal, undocumented knowledge is not scalable, auditable, or reliable for enterprise governance.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Classifying data only after a breach has already occurred</b>: reactive classification defeats the proactive purpose of asset management and leaves data unprotected beforehand.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-062","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"med","q":"A healthcare organization wants clinicians to access only the patient records of individuals currently under their direct care, dynamically changing as patient assignments change daily. Which access control approach is MOST appropriate?","options":["A static role granting all clinicians access to every patient record in the hospital","Attribute-based access control (ABAC) tied to current patient assignment records","No access control since all clinicians are trusted professionals","A single shared login for the entire clinical staff"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Attribute-based access control (ABAC) tied to current patient assignment records</strong> — ABAC can evaluate the dynamic attribute of current patient assignment to grant access only to relevant records, adjusting automatically as assignments change daily, which static roles cannot easily achieve.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A static role granting all clinicians access to every patient record in the hospital</b>: this grants excessive access far beyond the minimum needed for current patient care assignments, violating least privilege.</span> <span class='qd'><b>No access control since all clinicians are trusted professionals</b>: absence of access control does not scale, is not auditable, and violates regulatory expectations regardless of professional trust.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A single shared login for the entire clinical staff</b>: shared credentials eliminate individual accountability and violate basic identity management practices.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-063","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST illustrates defense-in-depth applied to authentication for a system holding sensitive personal data?","options":["Removing password complexity requirements to reduce user friction","Relying solely on a strong, complex password with no other control","Requiring strong passwords, MFA, and anomaly-based login monitoring together","Disabling account lockout to avoid support tickets"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Requiring strong passwords, MFA, and anomaly-based login monitoring together</strong> — layering multiple independent authentication and monitoring controls provides defense-in-depth, so that the failure of any single control does not fully compromise account security.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Relying solely on a strong, complex password with no other control</b>: a single control, however strong, lacks the layered redundancy that defense-in-depth requires.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Removing password complexity requirements to reduce user friction</b>: weakening a foundational control reduces overall security rather than adding depth.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling account lockout to avoid support tickets</b>: removing lockout protection eliminates a control against brute-force attacks.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-064","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"hard","q":"An access review reveals that 40% of employees hold entitlements to sensitive customer data that are unrelated to their current job function, accumulated through years of role changes. What is this phenomenon called, and what practice BEST addresses it?","options":["Federation; addressed by merging all roles into a single super-role","Zero trust; addressed by removing all authentication requirements","Data minimization; addressed by encrypting the entitlements database","Privilege creep; addressed through periodic, formal access recertification and role-based cleanup"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Privilege creep; addressed through periodic, formal access recertification and role-based cleanup</strong> — privilege creep occurs when users accumulate unnecessary entitlements over time through role changes without corresponding revocation; regular access recertification identifies and removes these unneeded permissions to restore least privilege.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Zero trust; addressed by removing all authentication requirements</b>: removing authentication would make the problem dramatically worse, not address privilege accumulation.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Data minimization; addressed by encrypting the entitlements database</b>: this scenario describes an access governance issue, and encrypting the entitlements database does not remove unnecessary access grants.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Federation; addressed by merging all roles into a single super-role</b>: consolidating into one broad role would further violate least privilege rather than correct it.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-065","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST reflects a defensible, risk-based approach to applying CIS Benchmark hardening guidance across a heterogeneous environment?","options":["Prioritizing hardening of systems processing the most sensitive personal data first, tailoring benchmark profiles to each system's role","Applying the exact same hardening profile to every system regardless of its function or data sensitivity","Ignoring CIS Benchmarks entirely in favor of vendor default configurations","Applying hardening only to systems that have already experienced a breach"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Prioritizing hardening of systems processing the most sensitive personal data first, tailoring benchmark profiles to each system's role</strong> — a risk-based approach focuses hardening effort where the potential impact of compromise is greatest, and tailors specific benchmark profiles (e.g., server vs. workstation) to each system's actual function.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Applying the exact same hardening profile to every system regardless of its function or data sensitivity</b>: a one-size-fits-all profile ignores differing risk levels and system roles, which is not the recommended risk-based practice.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignoring CIS Benchmarks entirely in favor of vendor default configurations</b>: vendor defaults are frequently insecure and are exactly what hardening guidance is meant to improve upon.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Applying hardening only to systems that have already experienced a breach</b>: this reactive approach leaves unbreached but equally sensitive systems exposed unnecessarily.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-066","domain":4,"obj":"4B6","diff":"med","q":"An organization is deprecating an older transport protocol version because it contains known cryptographic weaknesses that could expose personal data in transit. Which protocol is MOST likely being deprecated in favor of a newer, more secure version?","options":["HTTPS in favor of HTTP","An outdated version of TLS (such as TLS 1.0/1.1) in favor of TLS 1.2 or higher","IPv6 in favor of IPv4","DNS in favor of ARP"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>An outdated version of TLS (such as TLS 1.0/1.1) in favor of TLS 1.2 or higher</strong> — older TLS versions contain known cryptographic weaknesses and have been deprecated by standards bodies; organizations are expected to migrate to TLS 1.2 or 1.3 to protect data in transit.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>HTTPS in favor of HTTP</b>: this reverses the correct direction; HTTP is the insecure protocol being replaced by HTTPS, not the other way around.</span> <span class='qd'><b>IPv6 in favor of IPv4</b>: IP version adoption is about addressing and routing capacity, not transport-layer encryption for personal data.</span> <span class='qd'><b>DNS in favor of ARP</b>: these serve entirely different functions (name resolution vs. address resolution) and neither concerns transport encryption.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-067","domain":4,"obj":"4B7","diff":"hard","q":"Which key management practice reduces the impact of a single compromised encryption key on an organization's overall data protection posture?","options":["Storing all keys in a single unencrypted text file for simplicity","Using one master key for all systems indefinitely without rotation","Regular key rotation combined with limiting each key's scope to a specific system or data classification","Sharing the same key with all third-party vendors"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Regular key rotation combined with limiting each key's scope to a specific system or data classification</strong> — rotating keys periodically and scoping each key narrowly ensures that if one key is compromised, the blast radius is limited to a smaller subset of data rather than the entire organization.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Using one master key for all systems indefinitely without rotation</b>: a single unrotated master key maximizes the impact of any compromise across the entire environment.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Storing all keys in a single unencrypted text file for simplicity</b>: this creates a single, easily exploitable point of failure for all protected data.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Sharing the same key with all third-party vendors</b>: shared keys across vendors increase the risk surface and make it impossible to isolate a single vendor's compromise.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-068","domain":4,"obj":"4B8","diff":"med","q":"A retailer wants analysts to run aggregate sales trend analysis without ever seeing individual customers' full purchase histories tied to their identities. Which technique is MOST appropriate for this specific use case?","options":["Disabling analytics entirely to avoid any privacy risk","Deleting all transaction data before any analysis can occur","Sharing full customer names and addresses with every analyst for context","Pseudonymizing customer identifiers in the analytics dataset while retaining transaction-level detail needed for trend analysis"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Pseudonymizing customer identifiers in the analytics dataset while retaining transaction-level detail needed for trend analysis</strong> — replacing direct identifiers with pseudonyms allows analysts to study patterns and trends across transactions without directly seeing who each customer is, balancing analytical utility with privacy protection.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Deleting all transaction data before any analysis can occur</b>: this eliminates the ability to perform the requested trend analysis entirely, failing the business need.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Sharing full customer names and addresses with every analyst for context</b>: this exposes direct identifiers unnecessarily, contradicting the stated goal of not showing individual identities.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling analytics entirely to avoid any privacy risk</b>: this is a disproportionate response that ignores the legitimate business need and available privacy-preserving alternatives.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-069","domain":4,"obj":"4C1","diff":"hard","q":"During a log review, a privacy engineer finds that error messages returned to end users include full stack traces containing internal database queries with customer personal data embedded in SQL parameters. Which remediation BEST addresses both the security and privacy risk?","options":["Implement generic, user-facing error messages while logging detailed technical information only to a secured, access-restricted internal log store with sensitive fields masked","Display full stack traces to all users so they can self-diagnose issues","Remove all error handling so no messages are ever generated","Log the full stack traces to a publicly accessible web server for easy developer access"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Implement generic, user-facing error messages while logging detailed technical information only to a secured, access-restricted internal log store with sensitive fields masked</strong> — this remediation prevents information disclosure to end users while still preserving technical detail for legitimate troubleshooting, and protects sensitive fields even within the restricted internal store.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Display full stack traces to all users so they can self-diagnose issues</b>: this exposes sensitive internal data and query structure to any user, a serious information disclosure risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Remove all error handling so no messages are ever generated</b>: eliminating error handling harms usability and operational troubleshooting without properly addressing the underlying data exposure issue.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Log the full stack traces to a publicly accessible web server for easy developer access</b>: this makes the sensitive data even more widely exposed than the original problem.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-070","domain":4,"obj":"4C2","diff":"med","q":"A mobile app SDK from a third-party analytics vendor is found to be collecting device identifiers and cross-app browsing behavior without a corresponding disclosure in the app's privacy notice. What is the MOST appropriate engineering and governance response?","options":["Ignore the finding since the SDK is provided by a reputable, well-known vendor","Update the privacy notice to accurately reflect this processing and evaluate whether to restrict, reconfigure, or remove the SDK's tracking capability","Add more permissions to the app to compensate","Disable the app's privacy notice entirely since it is now inaccurate"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Update the privacy notice to accurately reflect this processing and evaluate whether to restrict, reconfigure, or remove the SDK's tracking capability</strong> — undisclosed tracking creates a transparency and compliance gap; the organization must both correct its disclosures and assess whether the SDK's behavior should be limited or removed to align with user expectations and legal requirements.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore the finding since the SDK is provided by a reputable, well-known vendor</b>: vendor reputation does not excuse undisclosed data collection or reduce the organization's own compliance obligations.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Add more permissions to the app to compensate</b>: adding permissions does not address the transparency gap and would likely increase, not reduce, privacy risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disable the app's privacy notice entirely since it is now inaccurate</b>: removing the notice entirely leaves users with no disclosure at all, which is worse than an incomplete one.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-071","domain":4,"obj":"4C3","diff":"easy","q":"A dataset is generalized so that all ages are grouped into 10-year ranges and all ZIP codes are truncated to the first three digits, ensuring every combination of these quasi-identifiers appears for at least 25 individuals. This is an example of applying:","options":["Differential privacy with epsilon=25","Homomorphic encryption","k-anonymity with k=25","Federated learning"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>k-anonymity with k=25</strong> — generalizing quasi-identifiers so that each combination of attributes is shared by at least k individuals (here, 25) is the defining mechanism of k-anonymity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Homomorphic encryption</b>: this is a cryptographic computation technique, unrelated to generalizing quasi-identifiers into ranges.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Differential privacy with epsilon=25</b>: differential privacy relies on calibrated noise addition governed by an epsilon parameter, not attribute generalization into groups of a minimum size.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Federated learning</b>: this is a distributed model training technique, unrelated to dataset generalization for anonymization.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-072","domain":4,"obj":"4C4","diff":"med","q":"A regulator asks an organization to demonstrate that a dataset it shared with a research partner is truly anonymized rather than pseudonymized. Which evidence would BEST support the organization's claim?","options":["Proof that direct name and email fields were removed from the file","A log showing the dataset was encrypted during transfer to the partner","A contract clause requiring the partner to keep the data confidential","Documentation showing no key, mapping table, or other means exists (held by any party) to re-link the data to specific individuals"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Documentation showing no key, mapping table, or other means exists (held by any party) to re-link the data to specific individuals</strong> — true anonymization requires that re-identification is not reasonably possible by any party; demonstrating the absence of any linkage mechanism is the core evidence needed to distinguish genuine anonymization from mere pseudonymization.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A log showing the dataset was encrypted during transfer to the partner</b>: encryption in transit protects confidentiality during transmission but says nothing about whether the data itself remains re-identifiable.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A contract clause requiring the partner to keep the data confidential</b>: a confidentiality obligation is a legal safeguard but does not establish that the data is technically anonymized rather than pseudonymized.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Proof that direct name and email fields were removed from the file</b>: removing only direct identifiers is insufficient; quasi-identifiers or retained mappings elsewhere could still allow re-identification, meaning this alone does not prove true anonymization.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-073","domain":4,"obj":"4C5","diff":"med","q":"Which statement accurately compares differential privacy to k-anonymity?","options":["Differential privacy provides a mathematical guarantee bounding any individual's influence on results, while k-anonymity is a syntactic property of a specific released dataset","k-anonymity and differential privacy are mathematically identical techniques","Differential privacy requires generalizing quasi-identifiers into equivalence classes, exactly like k-anonymity","k-anonymity provides a provable, adversary-independent mathematical guarantee, while differential privacy does not"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Differential privacy provides a mathematical guarantee bounding any individual's influence on results, while k-anonymity is a syntactic property of a specific released dataset</strong> — differential privacy offers a formal, provable bound on privacy loss regardless of an adversary's auxiliary knowledge, whereas k-anonymity is a structural property of a dataset (group size for quasi-identifier combinations) that can still be vulnerable to attacks using outside information.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>k-anonymity and differential privacy are mathematically identical techniques</b>: they are distinct models with different mechanisms (generalization/suppression vs. calibrated noise) and different guarantees.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Differential privacy requires generalizing quasi-identifiers into equivalence classes, exactly like k-anonymity</b>: differential privacy instead relies on adding calibrated statistical noise, not grouping records into equivalence classes.</span> <span class='qd'><b>k-anonymity provides a provable, adversary-independent mathematical guarantee, while differential privacy does not</b>: this reverses the actual strengths; differential privacy is the one offering the formal, adversary-independent guarantee.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-074","domain":4,"obj":"4C6","diff":"hard","q":"A privacy engineer reviewing an AI model deployment notices the model's confidence scores are exposed via the public API response. Why is this a privacy concern in the context of membership inference attacks?","options":["Confidence scores make the model run more slowly","Attackers can use variations in confidence scores between training and non-training samples to infer whether specific records were part of the training data","Confidence scores are always inaccurate and therefore misleading to users","Exposing confidence scores violates trademark law"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Attackers can use variations in confidence scores between training and non-training samples to infer whether specific records were part of the training data</strong> — models often exhibit subtly higher confidence on data they were trained on; exposing raw confidence scores gives attackers the exact signal needed to perform membership inference attacks.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Confidence scores make the model run more slowly</b>: exposing scores in an API response has no meaningful effect on model runtime performance.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Confidence scores are always inaccurate and therefore misleading to users</b>: accuracy of confidence scores is a separate model-quality issue, not the specific privacy attack vector described.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Exposing confidence scores violates trademark law</b>: this is an unrelated legal domain and has no connection to model inference privacy risks.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-075","domain":4,"obj":"4C7","diff":"med","q":"An organization plans to deploy facial recognition cameras in a retail store to identify repeat shoplifters. Which privacy engineering safeguard is MOST important to reduce risk to ordinary customers?","options":["Retaining all captured facial templates indefinitely for future use","Enrolling every customer who enters the store into the facial recognition system by default","Limiting the biometric watchlist strictly to individuals meeting a documented, legally supportable criterion, with strong access controls and defined retention limits","Sharing the facial recognition database with any requesting third party without restriction"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Limiting the biometric watchlist strictly to individuals meeting a documented, legally supportable criterion, with strong access controls and defined retention limits</strong> — scoping the sensitive biometric watchlist narrowly, securing access, and defining retention limits directly reduces the privacy impact on the general customer population who are not part of the legitimate security purpose.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Enrolling every customer who enters the store into the facial recognition system by default</b>: blanket enrollment of all customers is a disproportionate, high-risk practice far exceeding the stated shoplifting-prevention purpose.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Retaining all captured facial templates indefinitely for future use</b>: indefinite retention of biometric data violates data minimization and increases long-term breach exposure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Sharing the facial recognition database with any requesting third party without restriction</b>: unrestricted third-party sharing of biometric data creates significant, avoidable privacy risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-076","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"easy","q":"When assessing legacy infrastructure privacy risk, which factor is MOST relevant to prioritizing remediation efforts?","options":["The physical building's architectural style","The manufacturer's brand name","The color of the server rack","The sensitivity and volume of personal data the system processes"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The sensitivity and volume of personal data the system processes</strong> — prioritization should be risk-based, focusing limited remediation resources on systems handling the most sensitive or largest volumes of personal data first.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The manufacturer's brand name</b>: brand identity has no bearing on the actual privacy risk a system poses.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The color of the server rack</b>: this is a purely cosmetic attribute with no relevance to risk prioritization.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The physical building's architectural style</b>: architectural style is irrelevant to the data sensitivity a system handles.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-077","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"med","q":"An organization is comparing IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS models for a new project involving personal data processing. Which statement correctly reflects how the customer's privacy engineering responsibility changes across these models?","options":["Customer responsibility for infrastructure and platform-layer privacy controls generally decreases moving from IaaS to PaaS to SaaS, though data governance responsibility remains with the customer throughout","Customer responsibility is identical and unchanged across IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS","The customer has zero privacy responsibility once any cloud model is adopted","Customer responsibility increases from IaaS to PaaS to SaaS"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Customer responsibility for infrastructure and platform-layer privacy controls generally decreases moving from IaaS to PaaS to SaaS, though data governance responsibility remains with the customer throughout</strong> — as more of the technology stack is managed by the provider (IaaS to SaaS), the customer's technical control responsibilities shrink, but the customer always retains accountability for data governance, lawful use, and appropriate configuration.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Customer responsibility is identical and unchanged across IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS</b>: responsibility clearly shifts across the models as the provider manages progressively more of the stack.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The customer has zero privacy responsibility once any cloud model is adopted</b>: the customer always retains some responsibility, particularly for data governance and appropriate use, regardless of the cloud service model.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Customer responsibility increases from IaaS to PaaS to SaaS</b>: this reverses the actual trend; customer technical responsibility decreases, not increases, as more stack layers move to the provider.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-078","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"med","q":"A field service company equips technicians with ruggedized tablets that cache customer personal data locally to function offline. Which control BEST protects this cached data if a tablet is lost?","options":["Disabling all local caching, causing the app to fail without connectivity","Full-disk encryption on the device combined with remote wipe capability","Printing the cached data to paper as a backup","Storing the cache in an unencrypted, plainly named file for easy technician access"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Full-disk encryption on the device combined with remote wipe capability</strong> — encrypting the device's storage renders cached personal data unreadable without proper credentials, and remote wipe provides an additional layer of protection if the device is lost or stolen.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling all local caching, causing the app to fail without connectivity</b>: this defeats the legitimate offline business requirement rather than protecting the cached data appropriately.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Printing the cached data to paper as a backup</b>: paper copies introduce a new, harder-to-control physical exposure risk and do not protect the device's stored data.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Storing the cache in an unencrypted, plainly named file for easy technician access</b>: this makes the sensitive cached data trivially accessible to anyone who obtains the lost device.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-079","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"med","q":"Which statement BEST describes the privacy benefit of implementing egress filtering on a network that processes sensitive personal data?","options":["It eliminates the need for encryption entirely","It increases the speed of inbound data transfers only","It restricts and monitors outbound traffic, helping detect or prevent unauthorized exfiltration of personal data","It replaces the need for access control on internal systems"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>It restricts and monitors outbound traffic, helping detect or prevent unauthorized exfiltration of personal data</strong> — egress filtering controls what data can leave the network and to where, providing a critical layer of defense against data exfiltration even after other controls have been bypassed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>It increases the speed of inbound data transfers only</b>: egress filtering concerns outbound traffic control, not inbound transfer speed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for encryption entirely</b>: egress filtering is a complementary control and does not replace the need for encrypting sensitive data.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It replaces the need for access control on internal systems</b>: network-level filtering does not substitute for identity and access management controls on systems themselves.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-080","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"med","q":"A product team wants to launch a new feature that infers users' likely political affiliation from browsing behavior to personalize content, without disclosing this inference to users. Applying LINDDUN's 'Unawareness' category, what is the core privacy concern?","options":["The feature will slow down the recommendation algorithm","The feature will use too much server bandwidth","The feature is technically difficult to implement","Users are not sufficiently informed about this sensitive inference being made about them, undermining transparency and informed choice"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Users are not sufficiently informed about this sensitive inference being made about them, undermining transparency and informed choice</strong> — LINDDUN's Unawareness category addresses situations where data subjects lack adequate knowledge or control over how their data (including sensitive inferences) is being processed, which directly applies to this undisclosed profiling scenario.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The feature will use too much server bandwidth</b>: bandwidth consumption is a performance/cost consideration, not a LINDDUN privacy threat category.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The feature is technically difficult to implement</b>: implementation difficulty is an engineering effort concern, unrelated to the Unawareness threat.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The feature will slow down the recommendation algorithm</b>: algorithmic performance is unrelated to the transparency concern LINDDUN's Unawareness category addresses.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-081","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud-native application uses an API gateway in front of several backend microservices that process personal data. Which capability of the API gateway BEST supports privacy engineering objectives?","options":["Centralized enforcement of authentication, rate limiting, and field-level response filtering before requests reach backend services","Allowing every request to bypass authentication for faster response times","Removing all logging at the gateway layer to reduce noise","Exposing full backend error details directly to external API consumers"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Centralized enforcement of authentication, rate limiting, and field-level response filtering before requests reach backend services</strong> — an API gateway provides a consistent enforcement point for identity verification, abuse prevention, and controlling exactly which data fields are exposed to consumers, directly supporting data minimization and access control objectives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allowing every request to bypass authentication for faster response times</b>: bypassing authentication removes a critical control and increases exposure of personal data behind the gateway.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Removing all logging at the gateway layer to reduce noise</b>: eliminating logging removes visibility needed for security monitoring and incident investigation.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Exposing full backend error details directly to external API consumers</b>: this risks leaking sensitive internal implementation details and potentially personal data through verbose error messages.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-082","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"hard","q":"An enterprise data inventory shows 200 systems, but a network discovery scan reveals 235 systems actively communicating on the network. Which conclusion and next step BEST reflects sound privacy asset management practice?","options":["The discrepancy is immaterial and can be ignored since most systems are accounted for","There is a gap of unregistered ('shadow') assets; these 35 systems must be investigated, classified, and added to (or removed from) the governed inventory","The inventory tool must be broken and should be uninstalled","The 35 extra systems should be assumed to contain no personal data without verification"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>There is a gap of unregistered ('shadow') assets; these 35 systems must be investigated, classified, and added to (or removed from) the governed inventory</strong> — any discrepancy between the documented inventory and actual network reality represents unmanaged shadow assets that must be identified, classified for personal data content, and brought under governance or properly decommissioned.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The discrepancy is immaterial and can be ignored since most systems are accounted for</b>: even a relatively small number of unmanaged systems can pose outsized risk if they process personal data, so the gap cannot be dismissed as immaterial.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The inventory tool must be broken and should be uninstalled</b>: this jumps to an unsupported conclusion; the more likely explanation is genuinely unregistered assets, which is a common real-world finding.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The 35 extra systems should be assumed to contain no personal data without verification</b>: assuming safety without verification is precisely the risk that asset management processes are designed to prevent.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-083","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is a KEY advantage of ABAC over traditional RBAC in a large, complex organization with many data sensitivity levels?","options":["ABAC is always cheaper to implement than RBAC in every organization","ABAC eliminates the need for any authentication mechanism","ABAC can evaluate multiple contextual attributes simultaneously, reducing the need to create an unmanageable number of narrowly defined roles","ABAC requires no policy definition or governance"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>ABAC can evaluate multiple contextual attributes simultaneously, reducing the need to create an unmanageable number of narrowly defined roles</strong> — in complex environments, RBAC can suffer from 'role explosion' as combinations of conditions multiply; ABAC's ability to evaluate attributes dynamically at request time avoids this proliferation of static roles.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>ABAC eliminates the need for any authentication mechanism</b>: ABAC still depends on verified identity attributes and does not remove the need for authentication.</span> <span class='qd'><b>ABAC is always cheaper to implement than RBAC in every organization</b>: ABAC often requires more sophisticated policy engines and governance, and is not universally cheaper.</span> <span class='qd'><b>ABAC requires no policy definition or governance</b>: ABAC actually requires well-defined attribute and policy governance to function correctly, arguably more than simple RBAC.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-084","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"med","q":"An organization is designing step-up authentication for a customer portal. Under which circumstance would requiring an ADDITIONAL authentication factor be MOST appropriate, even for an already-authenticated session?","options":["When the session has been idle for less than one minute","When the user simply views their own already-displayed dashboard summary again","When the user logs out of the application","When the user attempts a high-risk action, such as changing banking details or exporting a full personal data record"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>When the user attempts a high-risk action, such as changing banking details or exporting a full personal data record</strong> — step-up authentication appropriately adds friction only at moments of elevated risk, such as sensitive transactions or bulk data exports, balancing security with usability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>When the user simply views their own already-displayed dashboard summary again</b>: routine, low-risk viewing of already-accessible information does not warrant additional authentication friction.</span> <span class='qd'><b>When the user logs out of the application</b>: logging out ends the session and does not require an additional authentication challenge.</span> <span class='qd'><b>When the session has been idle for less than one minute</b>: a brief idle period is not inherently high-risk and does not typically warrant step-up authentication on its own.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-085","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"med","q":"Which practice BEST demonstrates the application of least privilege combined with separation of duties for a database administrator role managing a system with sensitive personal data?","options":["The DBA can manage database performance and structure but requires a second approver to export bulk personal data or modify audit logging configuration","The DBA has unrestricted access to export, modify, or delete any data without oversight","The DBA shares login credentials with developers to save time","The DBA account is exempt from all logging since they are a trusted administrator"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The DBA can manage database performance and structure but requires a second approver to export bulk personal data or modify audit logging configuration</strong> — this design limits the DBA's standing privilege to necessary administrative tasks while requiring an independent check for particularly sensitive or high-risk actions, combining least privilege with separation of duties.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The DBA has unrestricted access to export, modify, or delete any data without oversight</b>: unrestricted, unchecked access directly violates both least privilege and separation of duties.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The DBA shares login credentials with developers to save time</b>: shared credentials eliminate individual accountability and violate fundamental identity management practice.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The DBA account is exempt from all logging since they are a trusted administrator</b>: privileged accounts require MORE monitoring, not exemption from logging, given their elevated capability.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-086","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"med","q":"An organization's hardening standard requires disabling unused network ports and services on all servers processing personal data. What is the PRIMARY privacy/security benefit of this control?","options":["It automatically encrypts all data on the server","It reduces the attack surface available to an adversary attempting to gain unauthorized access to personal data","It eliminates the need for any access control lists","It guarantees compliance with all applicable privacy laws"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It reduces the attack surface available to an adversary attempting to gain unauthorized access to personal data</strong> — every open port or running service is a potential entry point; disabling unnecessary ones directly shrinks the number of ways an attacker could exploit the system to reach personal data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>It automatically encrypts all data on the server</b>: disabling ports and services has no direct effect on whether data at rest is encrypted.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for any access control lists</b>: hardening complements, but does not replace, access control mechanisms.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It guarantees compliance with all applicable privacy laws</b>: hardening is one supporting control among many required for comprehensive legal compliance, not a guarantee on its own.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-087","domain":4,"obj":"4B6","diff":"med","q":"Which scenario BEST illustrates a privacy risk introduced by failing to properly validate TLS certificates in a mobile application?","options":["The app displays a certificate expiration warning to the user","The app loads slightly slower due to certificate validation overhead","An attacker performs a man-in-the-middle attack, intercepting personal data transmitted between the app and server despite apparent 'encrypted' communication","The server requires more storage to hold certificate files"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>An attacker performs a man-in-the-middle attack, intercepting personal data transmitted between the app and server despite apparent 'encrypted' communication</strong> — if an app fails to properly validate the server's TLS certificate (e.g., accepting any certificate), an attacker can present a fraudulent certificate and intercept supposedly encrypted traffic, exposing personal data in transit.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The app loads slightly slower due to certificate validation overhead</b>: performance overhead is a minor, unrelated operational concern, not the privacy risk of improper validation.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The app displays a certificate expiration warning to the user</b>: a legitimate expiration warning is actually a sign that validation is working correctly, not evidence of a validation failure risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The server requires more storage to hold certificate files</b>: certificate file storage size is unrelated to the security risk of skipping proper validation.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-088","domain":4,"obj":"4B7","diff":"med","q":"An organization encrypts personal data at rest using strong encryption, but grants all application service accounts full decrypt permissions on the key management system by default. What privacy risk does this create?","options":["Key rotation will no longer be technically possible","The data will decrypt more slowly than intended","The encryption algorithm will need to be changed entirely","Any compromised service account could decrypt all protected personal data, undermining the intended protection of encryption"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Any compromised service account could decrypt all protected personal data, undermining the intended protection of encryption</strong> — granting broad decrypt permissions to every service account defeats the principle of least privilege in key management, meaning a single compromised account can expose all encrypted personal data rather than a limited subset.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The data will decrypt more slowly than intended</b>: performance is unrelated to the access-control risk created by over-permissioned decrypt rights.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The encryption algorithm will need to be changed entirely</b>: the algorithm itself is not the problem; the issue is overly broad access to the keys.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Key rotation will no longer be technically possible</b>: broad decrypt permissions do not technically prevent key rotation from being performed.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-089","domain":4,"obj":"4B8","diff":"med","q":"A company wants call center agents to verify a customer's identity using the last four digits of their account number, without agents ever seeing the complete account number. Which technique BEST supports this requirement?","options":["Masking, displaying only the last four digits while storing the full number securely elsewhere","Full disclosure of the entire account number to every agent","Deleting the account number entirely from all systems","Sharing the account number over unencrypted internal chat for convenience"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Masking, displaying only the last four digits while storing the full number securely elsewhere</strong> — masking is specifically designed for this use case: agents see just enough of the value to perform verification while the complete sensitive number remains protected and inaccessible to them.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Full disclosure of the entire account number to every agent</b>: this exposes far more of the sensitive value than necessary for identity verification, violating data minimization.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Deleting the account number entirely from all systems</b>: deletion would break the ability to service the customer's account at all, failing the business requirement.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Sharing the account number over unencrypted internal chat for convenience</b>: this introduces an unnecessary and insecure channel for transmitting sensitive data.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-090","domain":4,"obj":"4C1","diff":"med","q":"Which monitoring practice BEST balances security visibility with privacy protection when logging user activity in an application handling sensitive personal data?","options":["Logging full names, national ID numbers, and health details in every activity log entry","Logging pseudonymized user identifiers and event types, with a separately secured process to re-link logs to real identities only when necessary for investigation","Disabling all activity logging to avoid any privacy concern","Publishing raw activity logs to a shared internal wiki for all employees to review"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Logging pseudonymized user identifiers and event types, with a separately secured process to re-link logs to real identities only when necessary for investigation</strong> — this approach preserves the security value of activity monitoring while minimizing routine exposure of directly identifying sensitive data, only re-linking identities under controlled, justified circumstances.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Logging full names, national ID numbers, and health details in every activity log entry</b>: this maximizes sensitive data exposure in logs, which are often less protected than primary systems.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling all activity logging to avoid any privacy concern</b>: eliminating logging removes critical security monitoring and incident response capability.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Publishing raw activity logs to a shared internal wiki for all employees to review</b>: broadly publishing logs internally creates unnecessary and uncontrolled exposure of user activity and any embedded personal data.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-091","domain":4,"obj":"4C2","diff":"med","q":"Which implementation detail is MOST critical to ensure a website's cookie banner produces legally meaningful consent under frameworks that require opt-in consent for non-essential cookies?","options":["The banner should automatically accept all cookies after five seconds if the user does not respond","The banner should be displayed in the smallest font possible to save screen space","Non-essential cookies must not be set until the user has taken an affirmative action to accept them","The 'reject' option should be hidden in a secondary menu that requires extra clicks to find"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Non-essential cookies must not be set until the user has taken an affirmative action to accept them</strong> — for opt-in consent regimes, the technical implementation must ensure that non-essential tracking cookies are blocked by default and only activated after a clear, affirmative user action, or the consent is not legally valid.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The banner should be displayed in the smallest font possible to save screen space</b>: minimizing readability undermines informed consent rather than supporting it.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The banner should automatically accept all cookies after five seconds if the user does not respond</b>: auto-accepting after a timeout is not affirmative consent and would not satisfy opt-in consent requirements.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The 'reject' option should be hidden in a secondary menu that requires extra clicks to find</b>: creating friction that disadvantages rejection undermines the fairness and validity of the consent mechanism (a 'dark pattern').</span>"},
{"id":"D4-092","domain":4,"obj":"4C3","diff":"med","q":"An organization plans to release an anonymized dataset of customer transactions for public research. Which risk should the privacy engineer evaluate BEFORE relying solely on k-anonymity as sufficient protection?","options":["Whether the dataset file size exceeds typical email attachment limits","Whether the file format is compatible with common spreadsheet software","Whether the dataset uses a modern character encoding standard","Whether combining the released quasi-identifiers with other publicly available datasets could re-identify individuals despite the k-anonymity guarantee"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Whether combining the released quasi-identifiers with other publicly available datasets could re-identify individuals despite the k-anonymity guarantee</strong> — k-anonymity alone does not account for linkage attacks using external datasets or protect against homogeneity/background-knowledge attacks, so evaluating re-identification risk from data linkage is essential before relying on it alone.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the file format is compatible with common spreadsheet software</b>: file format compatibility is a usability detail, not a privacy risk consideration.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the dataset uses a modern character encoding standard</b>: character encoding is a technical formatting detail unrelated to re-identification risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the dataset file size exceeds typical email attachment limits</b>: file size and distribution logistics have no bearing on the underlying privacy risk of the anonymization technique.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-093","domain":4,"obj":"4C4","diff":"med","q":"Which scenario correctly reflects data that has been pseudonymized but NOT anonymized?","options":["A dataset where names are replaced with employee ID numbers, and a secured HR system retains the mapping between IDs and names","A dataset where all identifying information has been irreversibly removed with no possible way to relink records to individuals","A dataset that has never contained any personal data at all","A dataset where every record has been permanently deleted"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A dataset where names are replaced with employee ID numbers, and a secured HR system retains the mapping between IDs and names</strong> — because the mapping between the pseudonymous ID and the real identity still exists and is retrievable, this data remains personal data under most privacy laws and is a textbook example of pseudonymization rather than anonymization.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A dataset where all identifying information has been irreversibly removed with no possible way to relink records to individuals</b>: this describes true anonymization, not pseudonymization, since no relinking mechanism exists.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A dataset that has never contained any personal data at all</b>: data that never contained personal data is not an example of pseudonymization at all, since there was nothing to pseudonymize.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A dataset where every record has been permanently deleted</b>: deleted data no longer exists and is not an example of either pseudonymization or anonymization technique application.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-094","domain":4,"obj":"4C5","diff":"med","q":"A privacy engineer is evaluating whether to use synthetic data or differential privacy for a specific low-risk internal software testing scenario that does not require statistical fidelity guarantees, only realistic-looking test inputs. Which factor would MOST reasonably favor choosing synthetic data generation over differential privacy in this case?","options":["Synthetic data is always mathematically superior to differential privacy in every use case","The primary need is realistic-looking test inputs for functional testing rather than a formal mathematical privacy guarantee for published statistical analysis","Differential privacy cannot be implemented on any dataset under any circumstances","Synthetic data always requires more computational resources than differential privacy in every scenario"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The primary need is realistic-looking test inputs for functional testing rather than a formal mathematical privacy guarantee for published statistical analysis</strong> — when the goal is simply generating plausible, non-real test data for internal QA rather than publishing statistically rigorous results with formal privacy bounds, synthetic data generation is often simpler and better suited than the more complex apparatus of differential privacy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Synthetic data is always mathematically superior to differential privacy in every use case</b>: neither technique is universally superior; the right choice depends on the specific use case and required guarantees.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Differential privacy cannot be implemented on any dataset under any circumstances</b>: this is factually incorrect, as differential privacy is a well-established and implementable technique across many contexts.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Synthetic data always requires more computational resources than differential privacy in every scenario</b>: resource requirements vary by implementation and are not a fixed, universal rule favoring one technique over the other.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-095","domain":4,"obj":"4C6","diff":"med","q":"Which practice would BEST help an organization detect that its production machine learning model's API is being systematically probed for a model inversion attack?","options":["Publishing the model's full training dataset for public download","Removing all authentication from the inference endpoint to simplify access","Monitoring and rate-limiting anomalous query patterns and volumes directed at the model's inference endpoint","Disabling all API request logging to reduce storage costs"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Monitoring and rate-limiting anomalous query patterns and volumes directed at the model's inference endpoint</strong> — model inversion and membership inference attacks typically require large numbers of crafted queries; monitoring for unusual query volume or patterns and applying rate limits helps detect and slow down such attacks.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Removing all authentication from the inference endpoint to simplify access</b>: removing authentication makes it easier, not harder, for attackers to launch inference or inversion attacks.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Publishing the model's full training dataset for public download</b>: this directly exposes the sensitive data the model's privacy protections are meant to safeguard.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling all API request logging to reduce storage costs</b>: disabling logging removes the very visibility needed to detect suspicious query patterns.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-096","domain":4,"obj":"4C7","diff":"med","q":"An organization is piloting consumer-grade smart speakers with always-listening voice assistants in shared office spaces. Which privacy engineering control BEST addresses the risk of inadvertently capturing sensitive conversations from non-users near the device?","options":["Disabling all software updates to keep the original factory configuration indefinitely","Enabling continuous audio recording and cloud upload with no wake-word requirement","Placing the devices in locations where employees are unaware of their presence","Configuring physical mute controls, limiting always-on listening to a clear wake-word trigger, and disclosing the device's presence and capabilities to everyone in the space"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Configuring physical mute controls, limiting always-on listening to a clear wake-word trigger, and disclosing the device's presence and capabilities to everyone in the space</strong> — combining technical limits on when audio is actually captured/transmitted with transparency to everyone who might be affected directly reduces the risk of capturing sensitive conversations from bystanders who have not consented.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Enabling continuous audio recording and cloud upload with no wake-word requirement</b>: this maximizes the risk of capturing unintended, sensitive conversations rather than limiting it.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Placing the devices in locations where employees are unaware of their presence</b>: covert placement undermines transparency and violates the reasonable expectation of notice for recording devices in shared spaces.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling all software updates to keep the original factory configuration indefinitely</b>: skipping updates leaves known security vulnerabilities unpatched and does not address the core listening/disclosure risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-097","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"hard","q":"A logistics company's delivery drivers use personal smartphones with a corporate app that accesses customer delivery addresses and signatures. The company does not manage the devices with an MDM solution. Which control BEST reduces privacy risk given this constraint?","options":["Implement application-level containerization (mobile application management) that encrypts and isolates corporate data within the app sandbox without requiring full device management","Require drivers to disable their smartphone's lock screen for faster app access","Store all delivery data unencrypted within the app's shared local storage for simplicity","Grant the app full access to the device's entire photo library and contacts by default"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Implement application-level containerization (mobile application management) that encrypts and isolates corporate data within the app sandbox without requiring full device management</strong> — mobile application management (MAM) can secure and isolate corporate data within the app itself, providing meaningful protection even on unmanaged, employee-owned devices where full MDM enrollment is not feasible.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Require drivers to disable their smartphone's lock screen for faster app access</b>: removing the lock screen significantly increases exposure of both corporate and personal data if the device is lost.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Store all delivery data unencrypted within the app's shared local storage for simplicity</b>: unencrypted, shared storage exposes sensitive customer data to other apps or anyone accessing the device.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Grant the app full access to the device's entire photo library and contacts by default</b>: this grants far more access than necessary for a delivery app's function, violating data minimization.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-098","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"easy","q":"Why is maintaining an accurate, current data flow map considered a foundational privacy engineering practice?","options":["It replaces the need for any encryption controls","It enables the organization to understand where personal data originates, moves, and is stored, supporting risk assessment and regulatory response","It is only useful for marketing department presentations","It guarantees the organization will never experience a data breach"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It enables the organization to understand where personal data originates, moves, and is stored, supporting risk assessment and regulatory response</strong> — data flow mapping provides the foundational visibility needed to apply appropriate controls, respond to data subject requests, and assess risk accurately across the environment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>It replaces the need for any encryption controls</b>: mapping data flows is a visibility exercise and does not substitute for actual technical protections like encryption.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It is only useful for marketing department presentations</b>: data flow maps serve critical operational, legal, and security purposes far beyond presentation materials.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It guarantees the organization will never experience a data breach</b>: no single practice, including data mapping, can guarantee the complete absence of future breaches.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-099","domain":4,"obj":"4B8","diff":"hard","q":"A payment processor wants to allow merchants to reference a customer's card for recurring billing without ever storing or transmitting the actual card number after initial capture. Which technique is SPECIFICALLY designed for this exact use case in payment card contexts?","options":["Basic data masking showing only the first six digits","Symmetric encryption using a key shared with every merchant","Tokenization, replacing the card number with a payment token that only the processor can map back to the real number in a secure vault","k-anonymity applied to the transaction database"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Tokenization, replacing the card number with a payment token that only the processor can map back to the real number in a secure vault</strong> — payment tokenization is purpose-built for this exact scenario, letting merchants reference a token for recurring transactions while the actual card number is stored only in the processor's secure vault, reducing merchant-side exposure and scope.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Symmetric encryption using a key shared with every merchant</b>: sharing a decryption key across many merchants creates broad exposure risk and defeats the purpose of limiting who can access the real card number.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Basic data masking showing only the first six digits</b>: masking is a display technique and does not provide a secure mechanism for repeatedly charging the same card without storing/transmitting the real number.</span> <span class='qd'><b>k-anonymity applied to the transaction database</b>: k-anonymity is a dataset-level statistical anonymization technique, not a mechanism for securely referencing an individual customer's payment method for billing.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-100","domain":4,"obj":"4C8","diff":"hard","q":"A hospital network wants to build a shared research consortium using patient data from multiple institutions to train a diagnostic AI model, while (1) never centralizing raw patient records, (2) protecting against membership inference on the trained model, and (3) providing a mathematically defensible privacy guarantee to its ethics board. Which combination of techniques BEST satisfies all three requirements together?","options":["Standard symmetric encryption of a centralized dataset with one shared key distributed to all institutions","A single shared spreadsheet of de-identified names emailed between institutions","Basic field masking of patient names only, with all other data centralized in one raw database","Federated learning across institutions combined with differential privacy applied to model updates during training"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Federated learning across institutions combined with differential privacy applied to model updates during training</strong> — federated learning keeps raw records local to each institution (satisfying requirement 1), while adding differential privacy to the shared model updates limits the influence of any individual patient's data and provides a formal, mathematically defensible bound against membership inference (satisfying requirements 2 and 3) — a well-recognized combination for privacy-preserving collaborative AI research.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A single shared spreadsheet of de-identified names emailed between institutions</b>: this centralizes data via email with no formal privacy guarantee and no protection against inference attacks on a trained model.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Basic field masking of patient names only, with all other data centralized in one raw database</b>: this violates the requirement to avoid centralizing raw records and provides no protection against membership inference on a trained model.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Standard symmetric encryption of a centralized dataset with one shared key distributed to all institutions</b>: this still requires centralizing the raw dataset and offers no mathematical guarantee against inference attacks on the resulting model.</span>"}
]);
